{{nihongo|'''''Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment'''''|ソードアート・オンライン －ホロウ・フラグメント－|Sōdo Āto Onrain: Horō Furagumento}} is a video game for the [[PlayStation Vita]] based on the ''[[Sword Art Online]]'' [[light novel]] series. It is the second video game in the series, the first being ''[[Sword Art Online: Infinity Moment]]''. The game was released in Japan on April 24, 2014, North America on August 19, 2014 and Europe and Australia on August 20, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bandainamcogames.eu/news/2014/07/02/new-details-on-sword-art-online-hollow-fragment/4461|title=New details on Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment!|publisher=[[Bandai Namco Games]]|date=July 2, 2014|accessdate=July 2, 2014}}</ref>

A "Director’s Cut" edition of the game titled ''Sword Art Online Re: Hollow Fragment'' was released on [[PlayStation 4]] within North America, Europe, Australia, and the Middle-East in July and August 2015,<ref name="ps4west">{{cite web|url=http://gematsu.com/2015/05/sword-art-online-re-hollow-fragment-lost-song-announced-ps4-coming-west|title=Sword Art Online Re: Hollow Fragment and Lost Song announced for PS4, coming west|publisher=Gematsu|date=May 27, 2015|accessdate=May 28, 2015}}</ref> and was released in Japan in November 2015.<ref name="Jun11DO">{{cite web|url=http://dengekionline.com/elem/000/001/066/1066699/|title=『SAO Re:－ホロウ・フラグメント－』＆『－ロスト・ソング－』最新情報が到着！ 前よりパワーアップした点は？|publisher=[[ASCII Media Works]]|date=June 11, 2015|accessdate=June 11, 2015|language=Japanese}}</ref> This version comes with new features, including an online play mode, additional bosses, the ability to play as a female character, among others.<ref name="Jun11DO" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2015/06/09/sword-art-online-re-hollow-fragment-will-let-you-make-a-female-protagonist/|title=Sword Art Online Re: Hollow Fragment Will Let You Make A Female Protagonist|publisher=Siliconera|date=June 9, 2015|accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref>

''Hollow Fragment'' was succeeded by ''[[Sword Art Online: Lost Song]]'', which was released in 2015 for the [[PlayStation 4]] and Vita.<ref name="ps4west" />

== Gameplay ==

The game has over 100 recruitable characters which can be chosen to accompany the player in the game's [[dungeon]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2014/02/24/can-befriend-100-characters-sword-art-online-hollow-fragment/|title=You Can Befriend Over 100 Characters In Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment|publisher=Siliconera|date=February 24, 2014|accessdate=May 2, 2014}}</ref> Gameplay combines elements of a [[MMORPG]]—albeit in a simulated fashion as it is not an online game,<ref name="gameinformer">{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2014/05/01/duo-of-sword-art-online-games-coming-to-north-america.aspx|title=Duo Of Sword Art Online Games Coming To North America|publisher=[[Game Informer]]|date=May 1, 2014|accessdate=May 2, 2014}}</ref> though it does include limited [[multiplayer]] via [[ad hoc]] for up to four players—as well as elements of a [[dating sim]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/news/view/133910-Sword-Art-Online-Hollow-Fragment-Arrives-in-North-America-this-Summer|title=Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment Arrives in North America this Summer|publisher=[[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]]|date=April 22, 2014|accessdate=May 2, 2014}}</ref>

== Plot ==

The game takes place in the same continuity as the prior game in the series, ''[[Sword Art Online: Infinity Moment]]'', which exists in an alternate storyline from the ''Sword Art Online'' anime storyline.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/infinity-moment-takes-everything-you-know-about-sword-a-464949599|title=Infinity Moment Takes Everything You Know About Sword Art Online, and Turns It on Its Head|publisher=Kotaku|date=April 2, 2013|accessdate=May 2, 2014}}</ref> The player controls the main character [[Kirito (Sword Art Online)|Kirito]], who has been trapped in the titular [[virtual reality]] [[MMORPG]] where dying in the game will lead to his death in real life as well.<ref name="gameinformer" /> Part of the game is actually a high definition recompilation of ''Sword Art Online: Infinity Moment'', the original game in the series released for the [[PlayStation Portable]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pocketgamer.co.uk/r/PS+Vita/Sword+Art+Online%3A+Hollow+Fragment/news.asp?c=59303|title=Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment will come bundled with another HD game for SAO fans|publisher=Pocket Gamer|date=May 1, 2014|accessdate=May 2, 2014}}</ref> including all content of "Floor Clearing" from the previous game<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2014/05/01/sword-art-online-hollow-fragment-includes-hd-version-sword-art-online-infinity-moment/|title=Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment Includes An HD Version Of Sword Art Online: Infinity Moment|publisher=Siliconera|date=May 1, 2014|accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref> with the addition of new unexplored "Hollow Area" of Aincrad.<ref name="SAOHF Announced for PS Vita">{{cite web|url=http://gematsu.com/2013/10/sword-art-online-hollow-fragment-announced-for-ps-vita|title=Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment announced for PS Vita|publisher=Gematsu|date=2013-10-06|accessdate=2014-04-02}}</ref>

== Development ==

The game was released on April 23, 2014 in Japan<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2013/10/08/sword-art-online-hollow-fragment-lets-players-hold-hands-heroine-tidbits/|title=Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment – Hold Hands With A Heroine And Other Tidbits|publisher=Siliconera|date=October 8, 2013|accessdate=April 3, 2014}}</ref> and May 29, 2014 in Taiwan, Hong Kong, as well as some Southeast Asian countries<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sg.news.yahoo.com/southeast-asia-enjoy-sword-art-online-hollow-fragment-121558031.html|title=Southeast Asia to enjoy Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment this end May|publisher=[[Yahoo!]]|date=May 2, 2014|accessdate=July 6, 2014}}</ref> with Chinese and English subtitles.<ref name="SAOHF Taiwanese Version">{{cite web|url=http://gematsu.com/2014/03/sword-art-online-hollow-fragment-will-english-traditional-chinese-subtitles-taiwan|title=Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment will have English and Traditional Chinese subtitles in Taiwan|publisher=Gematsu|date=2014-03-22|accessdate=2014-04-02}}</ref> It had also been announced that the game would be localized into English and released August 19, 2014 in North America<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bandainamcogames.com/game/sword-art-online-hollow-fragment.html|title=Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment|publisher=[[Bandai Namco Games]]|accessdate=July 4, 2014}}</ref> and August 20 in Europe and Australia. The American/European/Australian release will be [[digital distribution|digital download]] only.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2014/04/22/sword-art-online-hollow-fragment-coming-north-america-summer/|title=Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment Coming To North America This Summer|author=Ishaan|publisher=Siliconera|date=April 22, 2014|accessdate=April 22, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=SWORD ART ONLINE: HOLLOW FRAGMENT to be released in Europe and Australia|url=http://www.bandainamcogames.eu/news/2014/05/14/sword-art-online-hollow-fragment-to-be-released-in-europe-and-australia/4295|publisher=[[Bandai Namco Games]]|date=May 14, 2014|accessdate=July 22, 2014}}</ref> The game also received an update adding content extending the game's play time by 30 hours, including new areas, gameplay, and costumes, while also raising the level cap from 200 to 250.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2014/04/29/sword-art-online-hollow-fragments-major-update-adds-30-hours-content/|title=Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment's Major Update Adds 30 Hours Of Content|publisher=Siliconera|date=April 29, 2014|accessdate=May 2, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamezone.com/news/2014/08/12/sword-art-online-hollow-fragment-boasts-free-dlc-costumes-and-major-update|title=Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment boasts free DLC costumes and major update|publisher=GameZone|date=August 12, 2014|accessdate=August 19, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playstationlifestyle.net/2014/08/12/sword-art-online-update-hollow-fragment-major-update-arrives-september-2014-in-north-america-europe/|title=Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment Major Update Arrives September 2014 in North America, Europe|publisher=PlayStation LifeStyle|date=August 12, 2014|accessdate=August 19, 2014}}</ref> The game also features costume DLC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2014-08-14/sword-art-online-hollow-fragment-gets-free-costume-dlc/.77574|title=Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment Gets Free Costume DLC|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=August 14, 2014|accessdate=August 19, 2014}}</ref>

== Reception ==
{{Video game reviews
| MC = VITA: 67/100<ref name="MCVITA">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-vita/sword-art-online-hollow-fragment |title=Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment for PlayStation Vita Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=October 31, 2015}}</ref><br />PS4: 65/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-4/sword-art-online-re-hollow-fragment |title=Sword Art Online Re: Hollow Fragment for PlayStation 4 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=August 12, 2018}}</ref>
}}

The game sold 145,029 physical retail copies within the first week of release in Japan, topping the Japanese software sales charts for that week,<ref>{{cite web|title=Media Create Sales: 4/21/14 – 4/27/14|url=http://gematsu.com/2014/04/media-create-sales-42114-42714|publisher=Gematsu|date=April 30, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2014}}</ref> slightly outselling its predecessor, ''Infinity Moment'', which sold 138,180 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2014/04/30/this-week-in-sales-sword-art-online-hollow-fragment-begins-its-quest/|title=This Week In Sales: Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment Begins Its Quest|publisher=Siliconera|date=April 30, 2014|accessdate=May 2, 2014}}</ref> By July 2014, it outsold the previous game's total copies sold domestically,<ref name="cr-sequel">{{cite web|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2014/07/08-1/sword-art-online-hollow-fragment-game-sequel-being-discussed|title="Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment" Game Sequel Being Discussed|publisher=[[Crunchyroll]]|date=July 8, 2014|accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref> which is roughly 200,000 copies,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dengekionline.com/elem/000/000/842/842950/|title=『ソードアート・オンライン ―ホロウ・フラグメント―』大規模アップデート＆無料DLCの詳細が二見鷹介Pへのインタビューで判明 【SAOトゥデイ】|publisher=[[ASCII Media Works]]|date=April 24, 2014|accessdate=July 10, 2014|language=Japanese}}</ref> and sold more than 280,000 copies in Japan by December 2014.<ref name="dengeki-986405">{{cite web|url=http://dengekionline.com/elem/000/000/986/986405/|title=『SAO ロストソング』の情報も明らかに! 二見鷹介Pと河合泰一Pが語る2015年の目標は?|publisher=[[ASCII Media Works]]|date=January 13, 2015|accessdate=January 13, 2015|language=Japanese}}</ref> The game was the top selling digital Vita game on both the European region and North American region PlayStation Store in August and September 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.eu.playstation.com/2014/09/08/playstation-store-charts-august-infamous-first-light-diablo-iii-ros-fight/|title=PlayStation Store charts, August: inFAMOUS: First Light & Diablo III: RoS fight it out|publisher=Sony Computer Entertainment Europe|date=September 8, 2014|accessdate=September 8, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.us.playstation.com/2014/09/08/ps-stores-top-downloads-for-august-2014/|title=PS Store's Top Downloads for August 2014|publisher=Sony Computer Entertainment America|date=September 8, 2014|accessdate=October 22, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.eu.playstation.com/2014/10/09/playstation-store-charts-september/|title=PlayStation Store charts, September: Destiny, Minecraft & FIFA fight it out|publisher=Sony Computer Entertainment Europe|date=October 9, 2014|accessdate=October 15, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.us.playstation.com/2014/10/09/ps-stores-top-downloads-for-september-2014/|title=PS Store's Top Downloads for September 2014|publisher=Sony Computer Entertainment America|date=October 9, 2014|accessdate=October 15, 2014}}</ref> which added up to more than 450,000 copies sold worldwide<ref name="dengeki-986405" /> as of December 2014. Of these, approximately 90,000 copies were sold in Asia, and 70,000 copies were sold in North America.<ref name="dengeki-986405" />

The game received a ''[[Famitsu]]'' review score of 32/40.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gematsu.com/2014/04/famitsu-review-scores-issue-1324|title=Famitsu Review Scores: Issue 1324|publisher=Gematsu|date=April 15, 2014|accessdate=July 4, 2014}}</ref> An import review by ''PlayStation Lifestyle'' gave the Japanese version of the game a rating of 9/10, noting that the game provides plenty of hours worth of content and has no obvious performance issues which affect the gameplay experience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playstationlifestyle.net/2014/06/30/sword-art-online-hollow-fragment-review-go-virtual-vita-import/|title=Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment Review – Go Virtual (Vita Import)|publisher=PlayStation Lifestyle|date=June 30, 2014|accessdate=July 4, 2014}}</ref> The Asian version of the game which was localized into English and Chinese was noted by ''[[The Straits Times]]'' to contain various localization errors, such as grammar and spelling mistakes within the subtitled dialogue; nevertheless, the game was given a review score of 8/10.<ref>{{cite web|last=Tan |first=Colin |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/digital-life/gaming/story/sword-art-online-hollow-fragment-feels-real-mmorpg-20140611 |title=Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment feels like a real MMORPG |publisher=[[The Straits Times]]|date=June 11, 2014|accessdate=July 5, 2014}}</ref> The production team is said to be aware of the problems regarding the game's English translation and it have been stated that its sequel would be translated differently to produce a better translation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2014/10/29/sword-art-online-lost-song-producer-expect-better-english-translation/|title=Sword Art Online: Lost Song Producer: Expect A Better English Translation|publisher=Siliconera|date=October 29, 2014|accessdate=October 29, 2014}}</ref>

Following its release in the west, the game received mixed reviews. It has a score of 67 out of 100 on [[Metacritic]].<ref name="MCVITA" /> [[IGN]] awarded it a score of 5.5 out of 10, saying ''Sword Art Online''{{'s}} excellent combat is marred by a juvenile romance system, a horrible translation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2014/09/19/sword-art-online-hollow-fragment-review|title=Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment Review|publisher=[[IGN]]|date=September 19, 2014|accessdate=October 31, 2015}}</ref> [[Destructoid]] gave the game a rating of 7/10, noting that the game is solid and provides a fun experience, however may lack replay value,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.destructoid.com/review-sword-art-online-hollow-fragment-279631.phtml|title=Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment|publisher=Destructoid|date=August 19, 2014|accessdate=August 19, 2014}}</ref> while ''Gaming Age'' gave the game a "B" score, praising the game environment and mechanics, although noting that the camera controls feel flawed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gaming-age.com/2014/08/sword-art-online-hollow-fragment-review-ps-vita/|title=Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment review for PS Vita|publisher=Gaming Age|date=August 19, 2014|accessdate=August 19, 2014}}</ref> [[PlayStation Universe]] awarded it a score of 5.5 out of 10, saying "''Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment'' will only offer the most enjoyment to hardcore fans of the franchise that are willing to slog through the uninspired, tedious gameplay to get to the ample fan service on offer."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.psu.com/review/24494/Sword-Art-Online--Hollow-Fragment-Review/?page=2|title=Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment Review|publisher=[[PlayStation Universe]]|date=August 29, 2014|accessdate=October 31, 2015}}</ref> GameZone gave a rating of 8/10, praising the amount of content available within the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamezone.com/reviews/2014/08/19/review-sword-art-online-hollow-fragment-traps-fans-inside-an-mmo-simulator|title=Review: Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment traps fans inside an MMO simulator|publisher=GameZone|date=August 19, 2014|accessdate=August 19, 2014}}</ref> Twinfinite gave the game a 4/5, criticizing the steep learning curve and the dialogue translation, while finding the combat and game design to be positive,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.twinfinite.net/2014/08/19/sword-art-online-hollow-fragment-review/2/|title=Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment Review|publisher=Twinfinite|date=August 19, 2014|accessdate=August 19, 2014}}</ref> while Attack of the Fanboy referred to it as a solid RPG experience as long as one can look beyond the game's minor flaws.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://attackofthefanboy.com/reviews/sword-art-online-hollow-fragment-review/|title=Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment Review|publisher=Attack of the Fanboy|date=August 19, 2014|accessdate=August 19, 2014}}</ref> However, Hardcore Gamer rated ''Hollow Fragment'' a score of 1.5 out of 5, referring to it as a "bad game... the most debased, pandering garbage Japan has to offer... (a) rushed, broken, and imbecilic excuse for software" with "awful story, tedious combat, and inexcusable translation."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2014/08/19/review-sword-art-online-hollow-fragment/99686/|title=Review: Sword Art Online: Hollow Fragment|publisher=Hardcore Gamer|date=August 19, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819205635/http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2014/08/19/review-sword-art-online-hollow-fragment/99686/|archivedate=August 19, 2014|deadurl=no|accessdate=August 19, 2014}}</ref><!-- Per the Wikipedia policies of [[WP:NPOV]] and [[WP:NOTCENSORED]], content on Wikipedia must not be censored due to personal disapproval, and a fair balance of multiple points of view must be used with no bias towards either side to ensure neutrality. Censoring critical reviews and only permitting positive ones would produce a one-sided view, and thus violate Wikipedia's neutral point-of-view policy. If there are further concerns, discuss the matter on the article talk page. -->

